msgid "Examples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.lexsort:54
msgid "Sort names: first by surname, then by name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.lexsort:66
msgid ""
"Sort according to two numerical keys, first by elements of ``a``, then "
"breaking ties according to elements of ``b``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.lexsort:77
msgid "Compare against `argsort`, which would sort each key independently."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.lexsort:83
msgid ""
"To sort lexicographically with `argsort`, we would need to provide a "
"structured array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.lexsort:91
msgid ""
"The zeroth axis of `keys` always corresponds with the sequence of keys, so "
"2D arrays are treated just like other sequences of keys."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.lexsort:98
msgid ""
"Accordingly, the `axis` parameter refers to an axis of *each* key, not of "
"the `keys` argument itself. For instance, the array ``arr`` is treated as a "
"sequence of two 1-D keys, so specifying ``axis=0`` is equivalent to using "
"the default axis, ``axis=-1``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.lexsort:106
msgid ""
"For higher-dimensional arrays, the axis parameter begins to matter. The "
"resulting array has the same shape as each key, and the values are what we "
"would expect if `lexsort` were performed on corresponding slices of the keys "
"independently. For instance,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.lexsort:122
msgid ""
"Each row of the result is what we would expect if we were to perform "
"`lexsort` on the corresponding row of the keys:"
msgstr ""

